==Function==
This gene encodes a protein belonging to the raf/mil family of serine/threonine protein kinases. This protein plays a role in regulating the [[Mitogen-activated protein kinase|MAP kinase]]/[[extracellular signal-regulated kinases|ERK]]s signaling pathway, which affects [[cell division]], [[cell differentiation|differentiation]], and secretion.<ref name="entrez">{{cite web | title = Entrez Gene: BRAF | url = http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/entrez?Db=gene&Cmd=ShowDetailView&TermToSearch=673| accessdate = }}</ref>  

==Clinical significance==
Mutations in this gene are associated with [[cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome]], a disease characterized by heart defects, mental retardation and a distinctive facial appearance. Mutations in this gene have also been associated with various cancers, including non-Hodgkin lymphoma, colorectal cancer, malignant melanoma, papillary thyroid carcinoma, non-small cell lung carcinoma, and adenocarcinoma of lung.<ref name="entrez"/>  Some pharmaceutical firms have done basic research to develop specific inhibitors of B-raf protein for [[anticancer]] use.<ref>{{cite journal |author=King AJ, Patrick DR, Batorsky RS, Ho ML, Do HT, Zhang SY, Kumar R, Rusnak DW, Takle AK, Wilson DM |year=2006 |title=Demonstration of a genetic therapeutic index for tumors expressing oncogenic BRAF by the kinase inhibitor SB-590885 |journal=[[Cancer Res]] |volume=66 |issue=23 |pages=11100–5 |pmid=17145850}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Tsai J, Lee JT, Wang W, Zhang J, Cho H, Mamo S, Bremer R, Gillette S, Kong J, Haass NK, Sproesser K, Li L, Smalley KS, Fong D, Zhu YL, Marimuthu A, Nguyen H, Lam B, Liu J, Cheung I, Rice J, Suzuki Y, Luu C, Settachatgul C, Shellooe R, Cantwell J, Kim SH, Schlessinger J, Zhang KY, West BL, Powell B, Habets G, Zhang C, Ibrahim PN, Hirth P, Artis DR, Herlyn M, Bollag G |year=2008 |title=Discovery of a selective inhibitor of oncogenic B-Raf kinase with potent antimelanoma activity |journal=[[Proc Natl Acad Sci USA]] |volume=105 |issue=8 |pages=3041–6 |pmid=18287029}}</ref>  One such inhibitor, PLX4032, has been shown to cause [[apoptosis|programmed cell death]] in [[melanoma]] cell lines.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Bachelor |title=BRAF silencing by short hairpin RNA or chemical blockade by PLX4032 leads to different responses in melanoma and thyroid carcinoma cells |journal=Mol Cancer Res |date=May 2008 |volume=6|issue=5|pages=751–9 |pmid=18458053}}</ref> In a clinical study, PLX4032 was able to reduce numbers of cancer cells in over half of a group of 16 patients with advanced melanoma, and the treated group had a median increased  survival time of 6 months over the control group.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8076743.stm  | title=Drug hope for advanced melanoma | publisher=BBC News | accessdate=2009-06-07  | date=2009-06-02}}</ref><ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/22/health/research/22trial.html Target Cancer: A Roller Coaster Chase for a Cure,] By AMY HARMON, New York Times, Feb. 22, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/full/326/5960/1619 Melanoma Drug Vindicates Targeted Approach, Ken Garber, Science 18 December 2009, 326:1619, DOI: 10.1126/science.326.5960.1619</ref>
<ref>[http://www.asco.org/ASCOv2/Meetings/Abstracts?&vmview=abst_detail_view&confID=65&abstractID=34909 Phase I study of PLX4032: Proof of concept for V600E BRAF mutation as a therapeutic target in human cancer.] 2009 ASCO Annual meeting.</ref>PLX4032 has started phase 3 clinical trials.<ref>[http://clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/show/NCT00405587 Safety Study of PLX4032 in Patients With Solid Tumors] ClinicalTrials.gov</ref>

